The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation

 Security report by April 19

 OUR CORRESPONDENT

 Patna, April 12: Patna High Court today asked the Bihar police administration to file a detailed report on security provided to retired police officers and other VIPs in the state by April 19. 

 The court was hearing a petition filed by the Indian Medical Association on the law and order situation in the state.

 The division bench of acting Chief Justice Nagendra Rai and Justice S.N. Hussain directed the police headquarters in Patna to file a report on what grounds were houseguards, bodyguards and commandos deployed, the rules of deployment and the status of payment.

 Police today submitted a list of sensitive cases and criminals who faced serious charges for special hearing on a priority basis. They also informed the court that adequate steps have been taken to provide security to witnesses to be produced in courts in connection with the sensitive cases. 

 In another case, the court asked the administration to reply within three months on a petition filed by the Degree College Teachers? Association challenging the non-payment of a certain sections of teachers. 

 The court also asked the city police to report to it on a complaint by advocate Shashi Bhushan. The complainant had alleged that some policemen misbehaved with him during a raid on his house in the Kankarbag area of the capital.




